The N2 adsorption–desorption isotherms and the corresponding pore size distributions of the AHPCNs are given in Fig. 8
                     . After activation, the isotherms are changed from type IV of the HPCN-1: 3 to type II of the AHPCNs, in where the adsorption at P/P0 > 0.9 rapid rises with the increasing of KOH addition ratio. This demonstrates the meso- and macro-pore volumes of the AHPCNs are greatly expanded by severe chemical etching of the carbons. Moreover, the specific surface areas and the micropore volume of the AHPCNs are also enlarged (Table 4
                     ), which can provide more active sites for capacitive energy storage.
